**Slide Builder MVP Implementation Specification**

**1\. Objective**

Build a browser-first slide creation and presentation system in a Next.js app for a single company theme. The application is the primary runtime for authoring and presenting. PPTX export is a backup capability, not the system of record.

The MVP will support:

- Creating decks from structured slide templates
- Editing content in a guided, non-technical-user-friendly interface
- Uploading and using images stored in Supabase Storage
- Presenting decks full-screen from the app
- Exporting decks to PPTX as a fallback artifact

**2\. Product Principles**

- **App-native first**: the browser presentation is the canonical experience.
- **Structured templates over freeform canvas**: users edit approved layouts, not arbitrary coordinates.
- **Single source of truth**: deck content is stored as application JSON, never as PPTX.
- **Brand-safe by default**: one theme, locked typography, locked colors, fixed spacing rules.
- **Simple editing UX**: most edits happen through fields, inline editing, image selection, and reordering.
- **Export is an adapter**: PPTX generation translates application data into a backup presentation file.

**3\. Recommended Stack**

- **Framework**: Next.js App Router
- **Language**: TypeScript
- **Database/Auth/Storage**: Supabase
- **Rich text**: Tiptap
- **Validation**: Zod
- **Drag and drop**: dnd-kit
- **PPTX export**: PptxGenJS
- **Image optimization**: Next.js image pipeline for presentation/editor preview where appropriate
- **State management**: React state + server actions for MVP, or a light client store if needed

**4\. Architecture Overview**

The system is composed of five layers:

- **Deck domain model**
  - Theme definition
  - Template schemas
  - Deck JSON
  - Validation rules
- **Rendering layer**
  - React slide renderer for editor preview
  - React slide renderer for present mode
  - Shared layout primitives and theme tokens
- **Editing layer**
  - Deck shell
  - Slide list sidebar
  - Slide stage
  - Inspector panel
  - Inline editing hooks
  - Asset picker
- **Persistence layer**
  - Supabase Postgres tables for decks, slides, assets
  - Supabase Storage buckets for uploaded media and generated export files
- **Export layer**
  - Mapping from deck JSON to PptxGenJS
  - Template-specific export functions
  - Download endpoint or server action

**5\. Core Domain Model**

**5.1 Deck**

A deck is an ordered collection of slides with metadata.

export type Deck = {

id: string

orgId: string

title: string

themeId: 'company-default'

status: 'draft' | 'published' | 'archived'

aspectRatio: '16:9'

createdBy: string

updatedBy: string

createdAt: string

updatedAt: string

slides: Slide\[\]

}

**5.2 Slide**

Each slide is a discriminated union with template-specific fields.

export type SlideBase = {

id: string

type: SlideType

orderIndex: number

notes?: string

}

export type Slide =

| TitleSlide

| SectionSlide

| AgendaSlide

| TwoColumnSlide

| ImageCaptionSlide

| KPIGridSlide

| QuoteSlide

| ClosingSlide

**5.3 Rich Text**

Use Tiptap JSON for fields that need rich formatting. Restrict extensions to a minimal approved set.

export type RichTextDoc = Record&lt;string, unknown&gt;

**5.4 Theme**

Single company theme with locked design tokens.

export type Theme = {

id: 'company-default'

fonts: {

heading: string

body: string

}

colors: {

background: string

surface: string

text: string

mutedText: string

primary: string

secondary: string

accent: string

border: string

}

spacing: {

pagePaddingX: number

pagePaddingY: number

gapSm: number

gapMd: number

gapLg: number

}

typography: {

h1: number

h2: number

h3: number

body: number

small: number

quote: number

}

}

**6\. Eight Initial Templates**

These are intentionally conservative and broadly useful.

**6.1 Title Slide**

**Purpose**: deck opening

Fields:

- title: plain text
- subtitle: plain text
- eyebrow: optional plain text
- backgroundVariant: enum
- logoVisible: boolean

**6.2 Section Divider**

**Purpose**: transitions between sections

Fields:

- sectionTitle: plain text
- sectionSubtitle: optional plain text
- backgroundVariant: enum

**6.3 Agenda Slide**

**Purpose**: ordered overview

Fields:

- title: plain text
- items: array of 3 to 8 strings
- highlightIndex: optional number

**6.4 Two-Column Content**

**Purpose**: common body slide

Fields:

- title: plain text
- leftBody: rich text
- rightBody: rich text
- footer: optional plain text

**6.5 Image with Caption**

**Purpose**: image-led storytelling

Fields:

- title: plain text
- imageAssetId: string
- imageFit: 'cover' | 'contain'
- focalPointX: number
- focalPointY: number
- caption: optional plain text
- body: optional rich text

**6.6 KPI Grid**

**Purpose**: numeric highlights

Fields:

- title: plain text
- intro: optional plain text
- metrics: array of 2 to 6 items

Metric item:

- label: string
- value: string
- sublabel: optional string

**6.7 Quote Slide**

**Purpose**: pull quote / testimonial / key statement

Fields:

- quote: plain text
- attribution: optional plain text
- role: optional plain text
- backgroundVariant: enum

**6.8 Closing / CTA Slide**

**Purpose**: final page

Fields:

- title: plain text
- body: optional rich text
- ctaLabel: optional string
- ctaValue: optional string
- contactLine: optional string

**7\. UX Specification**

**7.1 Main Editor Layout**

Desktop editor layout:

- **Left sidebar**: ordered slide list with thumbnail previews
- **Center stage**: active slide preview at fixed 16:9 ratio
- **Right inspector**: fields for the selected slide
- **Top bar**: deck title, present, export, add slide

**7.2 Editing Interactions**

Required interactions:

- Create deck
- Rename deck
- Add slide from template picker
- Duplicate slide
- Delete slide
- Reorder slides via drag and drop
- Edit fields in inspector
- Click title/body fields inline for fast edits where practical
- Upload/select image from asset picker
- Edit image focal point within frame for image-based templates
- Add speaker notes per slide

**7.3 UX Constraints**

To preserve simplicity and quality:

- No arbitrary drag-anything-anywhere layout in MVP
- No user font selection
- No free color picker
- No rotation, arbitrary layers, or animation editor
- No collaboration features

**7.4 Present Mode**

Present mode requirements:

- Full-screen 16:9 slide viewport
- Keyboard navigation
- Click navigation support
- Presenter notes view optional for MVP, but notes storage should exist
- Smooth transitions kept minimal
- Mobile presenting out of scope for MVP

**8\. Storage and Persistence Design**

**8.1 Supabase Postgres Tables**

**decks**

- id (uuid, pk)
- org_id (uuid or text)
- title (text)
- theme_id (text)
- status (text)
- aspect_ratio (text)
- created_by (uuid)
- updated_by (uuid)
- created_at (timestamptz)
- updated_at (timestamptz)

**deck_slides**

- id (uuid, pk)
- deck_id (uuid, fk -> decks.id)
- type (text)
- order_index (int)
- content_json (jsonb)
- notes (text)
- created_at (timestamptz)
- updated_at (timestamptz)

**assets**

- id (uuid, pk)
- org_id (uuid or text)
- uploaded_by (uuid)
- bucket (text)
- path (text)
- filename (text)
- mime_type (text)
- byte_size (bigint)
- width (int, nullable)
- height (int, nullable)
- alt_text (text, nullable)
- created_at (timestamptz)

**deck_exports**

- id (uuid, pk)
- deck_id (uuid, fk -> decks.id)
- export_type (text) // pptx
- storage_path (text)
- created_by (uuid)
- created_at (timestamptz)

**8.2 Supabase Storage Buckets**

Create two private buckets:

- **slide-assets**
  - Stores uploaded images used inside decks
  - Paths scoped by org and deck or org only
- **deck-exports**
  - Stores generated PPTX files if exports are persisted
  - May optionally be skipped if exports are always streamed directly

Recommended object key patterns:

- slide-assets/{orgId}/{assetId}/{originalFilename}
- deck-exports/{orgId}/{deckId}/{timestamp}.pptx

**8.3 Access Model**

- Keep buckets private
- Use authenticated access for the editor
- Use signed URLs for temporary asset preview/download when necessary
- Use RLS on data tables and storage object access

**8.4 Upload Strategy**

For MVP:

- Standard uploads are acceptable for typical marketing and presentation images
- Enforce file type allowlist: png, jpg, jpeg, webp, svg if desired
- Enforce max upload size and validate dimensions
- Generate metadata row after upload succeeds

Future:

- Add resumable uploads if large asset handling becomes necessary

**9\. Validation Rules**

Validation should happen both client-side and server-side.

Examples:

- deck title required
- slide type required
- title length limits per template
- agenda item count between min and max
- metrics array within allowed bounds
- imageAssetId must exist and be accessible to org
- rich text allowed nodes and marks only

Recommended Zod approach:

- One base schema per template
- One discriminated union for all slide types
- One deck schema for full export validation

**10\. Rich Text Policy**

Use rich text only where it materially improves usability.

Allowed for MVP:

- paragraph
- bullet list
- ordered list
- bold
- italic
- link if needed
- hard break

Do not allow for MVP:

- arbitrary font sizes
- arbitrary colors
- tables inside rich text
- nested embeds
- pasted uncontrolled HTML styling

The editor should normalize pasted content into the approved schema.

**11\. Rendering System**

**11.1 Shared Slide Primitives**

Implement a shared set of primitives used by all templates:

- SlideFrame
- SlideHeader
- SlideBody
- SlideFooter
- RichTextBlock
- ImageFrame
- MetricCard
- QuoteBlock

**11.2 Fixed Stage**

Use a fixed virtual slide size, for example:

- 1600 x 900 logical pixels

Render all slides against that coordinate system using CSS layout. Scale the stage responsively in the editor and present mode.

**11.3 Overflow Handling**

Each template must define clear overflow behavior:

- clamp where acceptable
- shrink text only in tightly controlled ways
- display validation warnings in editor if content exceeds safe bounds

MVP rule: prefer warning users rather than implementing aggressive auto-fit logic.

**12\. PPTX Export Design**

**12.1 Export Philosophy**

PPTX is a fallback format. The export must be reliable and visually close, but not a perfect editable reproduction of app behavior.

**12.2 Export Strategy**

- Validate deck against schema
- Load theme tokens
- Create PptxGenJS presentation instance
- Define one slide master for the company theme
- Iterate over slides in order
- For each slide type, call a dedicated export function
- Write file and return download

**12.3 Export Function Contract**

Each template implements:

function exportTitleSlide(slide: TitleSlide, pres: PptxGenJS): void

or:

function exportTitleSlide(slide: TitleSlide, pptxSlide: Slide): void

Each function is responsible for:

- slide background
- title/subtitle placement
- logo placement
- images if present
- notes if supported later

**12.4 Export Scope for MVP**

Must support:

- text
- bulleted text
- images
- simple shapes/background blocks
- simple metric cards

Avoid in MVP export:

- advanced PowerPoint animations
- editable charts unless you explicitly build chart mapping
- complex text auto-fit behavior

**12.5 Export Execution Location**

Preferred approach:

- Generate PPTX on the server in a route handler or server action

Reasons:

- Keeps the browser lighter
- Easier to fetch and embed protected assets securely
- Easier to centralize export logging and failure handling

**13\. Image Pipeline**

**13.1 Accepted Formats**

- PNG
- JPEG
- WebP
- SVG optional, only if trusted and sanitized appropriately

**13.2 Image Metadata**

On upload, capture:

- width
- height
- mime type
- byte size
- uploader
- org scope

**13.3 Focal Point Support**

For image-based templates, support focal point editing:

- x from 0 to 1
- y from 0 to 1

Store focal point on slide content, not asset metadata, because usage may vary by slide.

**14\. API and Route Design**

**14.1 App Routes**

- /decks - deck list
- /decks/new - create deck flow
- /decks/\[deckId\]/edit - editor
- /decks/\[deckId\]/present - presentation mode

**14.2 API / Server Actions**

- createDeck(title)
- updateDeckMeta(deckId, patch)
- addSlide(deckId, templateType, insertIndex?)
- updateSlide(deckId, slideId, contentPatch)
- reorderSlides(deckId, orderedSlideIds)
- duplicateSlide(deckId, slideId)
- deleteSlide(deckId, slideId)
- createAssetUploadUrl(...) if using signed upload flow
- registerUploadedAsset(...)
- generatePptxExport(deckId)

