**Milestone 1: Foundation**

- Supabase schema and storage buckets
- Theme tokens
- Deck and slide schemas
- Deck CRUD
- Basic editor shell

**Milestone 2: Core Authoring**

- Implement all 8 templates in React
- Inspector panel controls
- Slide add/delete/duplicate/reorder
- Asset upload and selection
- Rich text editor integration

**Milestone 3: Presentation Mode**

- Full-screen present mode
- Keyboard navigation
- Basic notes support in model

**Milestone 4: PPTX Export**

- PptxGenJS integration
- Slide master definition
- Export support for all 8 templates
- Download flow
- Validation and error handling

**Milestone 5: Hardening**

- Overflow warnings
- RLS and storage policy review
- Analytics and error monitoring
- QA against real company content

**21\. Recommended Build Order for the First Two Weeks**

- Define theme tokens and 8 slide schemas
- Build deck list and deck editor shell
- Implement 3 templates first: Title, Two-Column, Image-Caption
- Add Supabase asset upload flow
- Add remaining 5 templates
- Add present mode
- Implement PPTX export for the first 3 templates
- Finish export for all 8 templates

**22\. Key Engineering Decisions**

- **Canonical model is JSON**
- **Presentation is app-native**
- **Templates are fixed and structured**
- **PPTX is a one-way export adapter**
- **Supabase Storage is private and accessed through controlled URLs/policies**

**23\. Open Decisions to Resolve Before Build Starts**

- Whether exports are streamed only or also persisted to deck-exports
- Whether notes are included in MVP present mode UI or stored only for later
- Whether SVG uploads are allowed in MVP
- Whether inline editing is enabled on all text fields or only headline/body fields
- Whether a deck can exceed a soft slide count limit in MVP

**24\. Final Recommendation**

Start with the most common deck flow and optimize for predictable quality:

- fixed company theme
- 8 templates
- structured content fields
- browser-first presentation
- server-side PPTX export

This will give the team a credible MVP without getting trapped in PowerPoint parity work.
